    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1981-01-15T17:41:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1981-01-15T17:41:00-05:00" n="345"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d345">
                <head>345. Telegram From the Embassy in Costa Rica to the Department of State<note
                        n="1" type="source" xml:id="d345fn1">Source: National Archives, <gloss
                            target="#t_RG_1">RG</gloss> 59, Central Foreign Policy File, [no film
                        number]. Secret; Immediate; <gloss corresp="#t_NODIS_1"
                        >Nodis</gloss>.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>San José</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1981-01-15T22:41:00+00:00">January 15, 1981, 2241Z</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>283. Subject: (S) Follow-up With <persName corresp="#p_COR_1">Carazo</persName>
                    on Cuban Activities. Ref: State 005249.<note n="2" xml:id="d345fn2">In telegram
                        5249 to San José, January 9, the Department instructed <persName
                            corresp="#p_MFFJ_1">McNeil</persName> to meet with <persName
                            corresp="#p_COR_1">Carazo</persName> in order to convince him to halt
                        Cuban clandestine activities in Costa Rica. (Carter Library, National
                        Security Affairs, Brzezinski Material, Country File, Box 12, Costa Rica:
                        6/80–1/81)</note>
                </p>
                <p>1. (S-Entire text)</p>
                <p>2. After having enlisted Foreign Minister <persName corresp="#p_NB_1"
                        >Niehaus</persName> in the cause, I saw President and <persName
                        corresp="#p_NB_1">Niehaus</persName> per instructions reftel on Nicaragua
                    and Cuba.</p>
                <p>3. He is sending <persName corresp="#p_NB_1">Niehaus</persName> to see <persName
                        corresp="#p_DBM_1">D’Escoto</persName> tomorrow (<persName corresp="#p_NB_1"
                        >Niehaus</persName> will follow the Venezuelan <persName corresp="#p_CBH_1"
                        >Calderon Berti</persName>, who concerted his approach to Nicaragua with
                        <persName corresp="#p_COR_1">Carazo</persName>). <persName corresp="#p_NB_1"
                        >Niehaus</persName> was instructed in my presence to tell <persName
                        corresp="#p_DBM_1">D’Escoto</persName> to stop intervention or face
                    consequences, isolation and loss of financial support from West, plus danger
                    from other <gloss target="#t_CA_1">CA</gloss> nations (i.e. Guatemala and
                    Honduras). <persName corresp="#p_CBH_1">Calderon Berti</persName> will have told
                    Nicaraguans that Venezuela will continue oil support ($30 million, according to
                        <persName corresp="#p_COR_1">Carazo</persName>) for Nicaragua only so long
                    as it behaves.</p>
                <p>4. I then made presentation on Cuba, saying that Cuban sponsored intervention in
                    El Salvador now offered perfect opportunity to throw them out. <persName
                        corresp="#p_COR_1">Carazo</persName> said he would not say yes or no now,
                    but would <pb facs="0903" n="852" xml:id="pg_852"/> consider it in the light of
                    public evidence developed on Cuban intervention.</p>
                <p>5. I will continue the effort.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_MFFJ_1">
                            <hi rend="strong">McNeil</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
